Harry Potter's Literary Magic
PRINCETON — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first edition of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) at literary festivals and bookstores. They have good reasons to do so.
Since June 26, 1997, when this young wizard first appeared, the "Boy Who Lived" has become a symbol of "resilience and endurance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into more than 70 languages, and sold over 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the book have earned a total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter theme toys and merchandise have brought in another $7 billion.
It is hard to imagine a day when readers of a certain age and with literary sensibilities will not be enchanted by Rowling's work.
Thus, I am always amazed to recall my students' terrible reaction to Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I had selected it for my course on popular literature at Princeton University. I have been teaching a series of courses on American bestsellers since 1993.
The course studies popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to consider why and how these bestsellers attract their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask my students to choose a final work that represents the popular taste of the period.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, Harry Potter fever hit the US coast hard.
In June, the American publisher of the series rushed Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, the second book in the series, into stores in hardcover.
The institution also published Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, the third book in the series, along with a paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone, on September 8.
By the end of the month, Rowling’s novels dominated the New York Times Best Sellers list for hardcover fiction, while the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone topped the bestseller list for paperbacks.
Time even put the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image can be seen everywhere.
My students couldn't wait to find out why such enthusiasm existed.
Oh dear, they were utterly disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing but second-rate nonsense, far inferior to classics like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they treasured from their childhood.
Though only a few years had passed since their childhood, they criticized Harry Potter as many notorious adult critics did—calling it "plagiarized," "poorly written," "cliché-ridden," and "annoying."

In their view, Harry possessed neither magic nor ingenuity nor warmth.
Their disgust surprised me, but in retrospect, there was nothing particularly remarkable about it.
Although adults formed a large part of the Harry Potter audience from the very start, these students were simply in the wrong age bracket to objectively grasp the phenomenon.
They were too old to accept new children’s literature but still too young to have their own children (I had just become a parent myself), and they eagerly insisted that while the Harry series was now immensely popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of the following year, 2000, the next batch of students also chose Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone as their final analysis book, just like their peers before them, they confidently refused to accept this work.
Let's fast-forward to spring 2007.
After putting the course on hold for a few years, I taught "American Bestsellers" again.
When the students chose their final analysis book, they picked Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.
And I was prepared for their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first encountered Rowling's works as teenagers rather than college students, just beginning their teenage years. This means they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened in autumn 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry ever disappear from our memories?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught a bestseller course twice, and on both occasions, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Are they tired of Potter?
From the comments on the Harry Potter books in another course I teach, "Children's Literature," where Rowling's works are discussed, this seems unlikely.
Now, I choose to include a Harry Potter novel in my syllabus, but not "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," which is typically very popular, but rather "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" – my favorite book in the Harry Potter series of seven, which marks the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex descriptions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also loved this book.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I conduct a survey first: "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% had read Harry Potter and Azkaban Prisoner.
In 2012, that number rose to 94%.
But the percentage continued to decline thereafter – it was 87% in 2014 and dropped to 81% in 2016.
This is not science, I know.
But I wonder: will the proportion of students who have read Harry Potter fall below 80% when I teach "Children's Literature" next spring?
Will it turn out that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continually declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead where the percentage stabilizes and no longer declines?
Maybe Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am happy to continue inviting him into my classroom.
